{"id":"1101.2630","submitter":"Bojan Mohar","authors":"Matt DeVos, Zden\\v{e}k Dvo\\v{r}\\'ak, Jacob Fox, Jessica McDonald,\n  Bojan Mohar, Diego Scheide","title":"Minimum degree condition forcing complete graph immersion","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An immersion of a graph $H$ into a graph $G$ is a one-to-one mapping $f:V(H)\n\\to V(G)$ and a collection of edge-disjoint paths in $G$, one for each edge of\n$H$, such that the path $P_{uv}$ corresponding to edge $uv$ has endpoints\n$f(u)$ and $f(v)$. The immersion is strong if the paths $P_{uv}$ are internally\ndisjoint from $f(V(H))$. It is proved that for every positive integer $t$,\nevery simple graph of minimum degree at least $200t$ contains a strong\nimmersion of the complete graph $K_t$. For dense graphs one can say even more.\nIf the graph has order $n$ and has $2cn^2$ edges, then there is a strong\nimmersion of the complete graph on at least $c^2 n$ vertices in $G$ in which\neach path $P_{uv}$ is of length 2. As an application of these results, we\nresolve a problem raised by Paul Seymour by proving that the line graph of\nevery simple graph with average degree $d$ has a clique minor of order at least\n$cd^{3/2}$, where $c>0$ is an absolute constant.\n  For small values of $t$, $1\\le t\\le 7$, every simple graph of minimum degree\nat least $t-1$ contains an immersion of $K_t$ (Lescure and Meyniel, DeVos et\nal.). We provide a general class of examples showing that this does not hold\nwhen $t$ is large.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Jan 2011 18:28:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-01-14"}
